Here’s what caught our attention on Thursday: 1. June Producer Price Inflation The producer price inflation (PPI) for June is expected to be released on Thursday. In May, PPI rose 4.6% year-on-year, the highest since January. In April PPI was at 4%. South Africa’s PPI averaged 5.69% from 2013 until 2018, data from Trading Economics shows. Update to follow. 2. Day two of the Brics summit When a trade war is looming in the West, the people in the South react. The five-member congregation meeting in South Africa are discussing ways to strengthen trade and ties between them to avoid giving all power to US president, Donald Trump and his bid to increase trade tariffs. On Wednesday, Chinese President Xi Jinping called on all members of Brics, namely, Brazil, Russia, India, China and South Africa to reject the trade war and to jointly reject unilateralism and protectionism. Read: Xi calls for a rejection of trade wars 3. Nedbank results Nedbank is reporting that for the first half of 2018, basic earnings per share is expected to be between 1344.4 cents and 1399.0 cents or increase between 23% and 28%. Headline earnings per share is expected to be between 1350.5 cents and 1405.4 cents, which is an increase of 23% and 28%. The bank says it delivered a strong performance over the period, assisted by its ‘share of associated income from Ecobank as it returned profitability.’ Nedbank’s results, for the six months ended June 30, 2018, are expected to be released on August 7 2018. 4. Anglo American results For the six months ended June 30, 2018, mining company Anglo American is reporting an 11% increase in underlying Ebitda to $4.6 billion and a 19% return on capital employed. The company says it also managed to strengthen its balance sheet as net debt is down $4 billion. The mining giant says the interim dividend increased 2% to $0.49 per share, earnings per share decreased 6% to $1.02 and underlying earnings per share increased 3% to $1.23. 5. Behind the Chinese’s lending When President Cyril Ramaphosa announced the outcome of his meeting with Chinese President Xi Jinping on Tuesday, South Africa was quick to react. China said it would invest $14.7 billion in South Africa, and loan state-owned entity Eskom and Transnet R33.2 billion and R4 billion respectively. As far as it is known, the loans are being described as “normal commercial loans”, which are guaranteed by the government. Moneyweb is reporting that the Eskom loan is repayable in 15 years, and the Transnet loan is repayable within five-and-a-half years. The interest rate at which it will be repaid, has not been disclosed. Read the full story here: Pressure mounts for Eskom, Transnet to reveal Chinese loan terms Thursday news bonus: